{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17620091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17620091"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:40:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:40:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16614"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16614"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.36,0.45,0.05,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9305"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76216"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9305"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16614"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61720"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5241"},{"type":"tags","id":"7614"},{"type":"tags","id":"7652"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22058"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22065"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76216"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPlatinum-based chemotherapy agents are widely used in the treatment of solid tumours, including testicular cancer, ovarian cancer, and lung cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism by which platinum compounds kill cancer cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Selective accumulation in tumour tissue","Cell cycle arrest in G1 phase","Formation of DNA crosslinks leading to cell death","Inhibition of tumour blood vessel growth","Stimulation of immune response"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPlatinum compounds work primarily through \u003Cstrong\u003Eformation of DNA crosslinks leading to cell death\u003C/strong\u003E. These drugs bind to guanine bases in DNA, creating crosslinks that prevent DNA replication and transcription. Since cancer cells divide more frequently than most normal cells, they are particularly vulnerable to this mechanism of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelective accumulation in tumour tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - platinum compounds distribute throughout the body and are not specifically concentrated in tumour tissue\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECell cycle arrest in G1 phase\u003C/strong\u003E - DNA crosslinking affects cells in multiple phases of the cell cycle, not just G1\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of tumour blood vessel growth\u003C/strong\u003E - this describes the mechanism of anti-angiogenic drugs, not platinum compounds\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulation of immune response\u003C/strong\u003E - while platinum compounds may have some immunological effects, this is not their primary mechanism of action\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe effectiveness of platinum compounds against solid tumours stems from the vulnerability of rapidly proliferating cancer cells to DNA damage, which triggers programmed cell death through apoptosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Platinum compounds form DNA crosslinks by binding to guanine bases, preventing DNA replication and transcription.","Solid tumours are 